    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided text, here are the significant accounting policies disclosed by the company, categorized by the specific areas you requested:\n\n### 1. Revenue Recognition\nRevenue recognition policies are detailed by segment and revenue type:\n*   **Advertising (AI Segment):** Revenue is recognized in the period the ad is delivered and user engagement criteria are met. The company acts as principal and recognizes revenue **gross** for ads sold directly through its X platform. For ads sold through Supply Side Platform (SSP) partners, the company acts as an agent and recognizes revenue **net** (based on a percentage share of gross ad spend).\n*   **Subscriptions:** Revenue is recognized ratably over the period of the subscription term.\n*   **Data Licensing:** Customers are granted rights to access, search, and analyze IP. Revenue is recognized on a straight-line basis for fixed monthly fee arrangements with a single future IP obligation. For arrangements with minimum guarantees, the minimum is recognized straight-line over the period, and any excess royalties are recognized over the contract term on a cumulative straight-line basis. \n*   **API Services:** For stand-ready subscription access, revenue is recognized ratably on a straight-line basis. For usage-based arrangements, revenue is recognized as services are consumed (i.e., tokens processed or compute hours utilized).\n*   **Space Segment:** \n    *   *Launch Services:* Revenue is recognized at a **point in time** (upon launch/deployment to intended orbit) due to the interchangeability of flight hardware.\n    *   *Launch and Development:* Revenue is recognized **over time** using the cost-to-cost input method, as the company\'s performance creates an asset with no alternative use and there is an enforceable right to payment.\n*   **Connectivity Segment:** \n    *   *Broadband & Mobile:* Revenue is recognized over time either ratably over the subscription term or based on actual data usage. \n    *   *Starshield:* Revenue is recognized over time using the cost-to-cost input method for long-term contracts.\n    *   *Starlink Kits:* Revenue is recognized at a **point in time** when control transfers to the customer (upon delivery or installation).\n*   **Other Policies:** Taxes collected from customers and remitted to government authorities are excluded from the transaction price. Sales commissions are expensed as incurred if the amortization period is one year or less.\n\n### 2. Cost of Revenues\n*   **General Composition:** Includes cost of materials, depreciation and amortization, shipping and handling, payment processor fees, customs and duties, revenue share costs, infrastructure costs (rocket, kit, satellite manufacturing, data centers, colocation, public cloud), allocated overhead, and employee compensation (salaries, benefits, share-based compensation).\n*   **Payment Processing Fees:** For all segments, credit card payment processing fees are recorded within Cost of revenue.\n*   **Connectivity Segment Specifics:** Cost of revenue includes depreciation (launch, satellite, ground infrastructure), Starlink Kit costs, shipping/handling, ground operating expenses, employee compensation, payment processor fees, warranty expense, inventory excess and obsolescence, and customs/duties.\n*   **Warranties:** The company offers a 1-to-2-year standard product warranty on Starlink Kits. An estimate of future warranty costs is recorded as a component of Cost of revenue at the time revenue is recognized, based on historical and current product failure rates (though warranty expenses and liabilities are deemed immaterial).\n\n### 3. Intersegment Revenues\n*   The company **does not recognize inter-segment revenue** for launches of its own Starlink satellites. Instead, those launch costs are capitalized in satellites within "Property, plant, and equipment, net." \n*   While launch capacity is allocated to the Connectivity segment (and expected to be allocated to the AI segment in the future), the Space segment revenue strictly reflects external customer launches and customer activities.\n\n### 4. Multi-Element Arrangements and Bundled Products\n*   **Starlink Customer Contracts:** Substantially all contracts with Starlink customers contain multiple performance obligations, typically bundling (i) broadband services and (ii) the Starlink Kit hardware. The transaction price is allocated to each distinct performance obligation based on its standalone selling price (determined by the price the good/service is sold separately to similar customers).\n*   **Data Licensing:** For arrangements containing multiple performance obligations, revenue is allocated on a relative basis between the obligations based on standalone selling prices derived from directly observable standalone transactions.\n*   **Shipping and Handling:** Shipping and handling charges are included in the transaction price, but the company recognizes shipping and handling activities as fulfillment activities rather than separate performance obligations.\n\n### 5. Inventory\n*   While a comprehensive inventory capitalization policy is not fully detailed, the text notes that management uses estimates and significant judgment to determine "reserves for excess and obsolete inventory." Furthermore, "inventory excess and obsolescence" is explicitly listed as a component of the Connectivity segment\'s cost of revenue.\n\n### 6. Long-Lived Assets\n*   **Useful Lives and Valuations:** Management exercises significant judgment and estimation regarding the useful lives of property, plant, and equipment, as well as the fair value of indefinite-lived intangible assets and goodwill.\n*   **Leases (ROU Assets):** Upon lease commencement, the company recognizes a right-of-use (ROU) asset and lease liability. Operating lease expense is recognized on a straight-line basis. Finance leases are split into an interest component (recorded in Interest expense) and an amortization component (recorded in Cost of revenue, R&D, or SG&A). Because leases generally do not provide an implicit rate, the company uses an estimated incremental borrowing rate to calculate the present value of future lease obligations.',
