        output='Based on the provided financial statement notes and prospectus excerpts, here is the disclosure regarding the capitalization of satellite costs, useful lives, and the accounting treatment for orbital AI compute satellites and the AI segment\'s orbital activities:\n\n**Capitalization of Satellite Costs**\nThe Company capitalizes satellites as part of its Property, plant, and equipment. The capitalized costs include:\n*   Costs to build the satellites (parts, labor, and allocated overhead).\n*   Capitalized launch costs incurred by the Space segment to launch the satellites into orbit, which include an allocation of the flight vehicle costs.\n*   Significant refurbishment, renewals, and enhancements that increase the functionality, output, or expected life of a satellite are capitalized and depreciated ratably over the identified useful life. Routine maintenance and repairs are expensed as incurred.\n*   The Company also capitalizes certain interest costs associated with the significant acquisition or construction of long-term assets, ceasing capitalization once the asset is substantially completed and ready for its intended use. \n\n**Useful Lives of Satellites**\nThe estimated useful lives for satellite assets are as follows:\n*   **Broadband satellites:** 5-year useful life.\n*   **First-generation mobile satellites:** 3-year useful life.\n*   **General satellite category:** 3 to 5 years.\n\nManagement estimates useful lives based on engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, design enhancements across generations, and planned transitions to newer technology. Factors considered include on-orbit performance, orbit-raise timing, expected service capability, and the evolution of constellation density and technology. If management determines useful lives are shorter or longer than originally estimated, the depreciation rate is adjusted prospectively.\n\n**Orbital AI Compute Satellites and In-Space Assets**\nThe prospectus defines an "AI compute satellite" as a satellite equipped with onboard artificial intelligence processing capabilities designed to perform data analysis, inference, or other machine learning workloads in orbit. The Company expects to begin deploying these orbital AI compute satellites as early as 2028. \n\nHowever, the provided text **does not specify a distinct or separate accounting treatment** exclusively for orbital AI compute satellites or in-space assets. Instead, the disclosures suggest these assets will be accounted for under the Company\'s existing policies:\n*   The Company notes that its expertise in terrestrial modular data center architectures "will provide a foundation for the deployment of compute infrastructure in orbit given similarities in form factor." Terrestrial servers and networking equipment currently have an estimated useful life of 5 to 6 years.\n*   Like all Property, plant, and equipment, in-space assets would be evaluated for impairment at the lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities whenever events or circumstances indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable.\n\n**Accounting for the AI Segment\'s Orbital Compute Activities**\nThe provided text does not contain a specific accounting policy detailing how the AI segment\'s orbital compute activities (such as revenue recognition or specialized R&D capitalization) will be handled. The disclosures focus primarily on the strategic intent—leveraging reusable rockets and low-cost satellite manufacturing to build a coherent constellation of compute in orbit—and note that these activities are subject to significant technical complexity, capital requirements, and regulatory approvals. From an accounting perspective, the infrastructure falls under the broader Property, plant, and equipment capitalization and impairment policies noted above.',
