    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output="Based on the provided financial statement excerpts, here is the disclosure regarding research and development expenses, capitalized internal-use software, development cost capitalization policies, and the accounting for shared infrastructure across segments:\n\n**Research and Development (R&D) Expenses**\n*   **General Policy:** The Company sponsors various R&D projects, and all associated costs are expensed as incurred. R&D expenses consist of materials, employee compensation (salaries, benefits, share-based compensation), contractor compensation, cloud computing, data services, equipment leases, depreciation for R&D equipment, and allocated overhead. \n*   **Engineering Services:** R&D costs also include expenses related to developing features and modules created through engineering services for the Company’s products (e.g., Falcon vehicles), provided the Company retains the associated intellectual property.\n*   **Space Segment (Starship):** Space segment R&D expenses primarily relate to the development, build, and testing of Starship. Because Starship is currently in the development stage, a majority of its costs (test flight hardware, Raptor engines, compensation, tooling, etc.) are expensed to R&D as incurred. \n\n**Capitalizing Development Costs for New Products/Technologies**\n*   **Software Development Costs:** The Company expenses software development costs marketed under on-premise perpetual license agreements. Costs incurred prior to establishing technological feasibility are expensed as R&D. Because technological feasibility typically occurs shortly before general release, all software development costs for the years ended December 31, 2025, 2024, and 2023 were expensed as incurred.\n*   **Starship Commercialization:** The Company expects Space R&D to increase as it invests in the commercialization of Starship. Once Starship is commercialized by delivering payload to orbit, Starship costs will generally be capitalized and then depreciated in the cost of revenue of the segment associated with the payload delivered.\n\n**Capitalized Internal-Use Software**\n*   While the text does not detail the Company's current capitalization policy for internal-use software, it discloses the recent issuance of FASB ASU No. 2025-06, *Targeted Improvements to the Accounting for Internal-Use Software*. This ASU simplifies capitalization guidance by removing prescriptive and sequential software development stages. The Company is currently evaluating the provisions of this ASU but does not expect its adoption to have a material impact on its consolidated financial statements.\n\n**Accounting for Assets Spanning Multiple Segments / Shared Infrastructure**\n*   **Inter-segment Launch Capacity:** The Space segment allocates a significant amount of launch capacity to the Connectivity segment (for Starlink satellites) and expects to allocate significant capacity to the AI segment in the future. \n*   **Capitalization of Shared Launch Costs:** For launches of its own Starlink satellites, the Company does not recognize inter-segment revenue. Instead, the launch costs incurred by the Space segment are capitalized as satellites within *Property, plant, and equipment, net* for the Connectivity segment. These capitalized satellite costs include an allocation of the flight vehicle hardware costs.\n*   **Overhead Allocation:** Shared launch operations and overhead costs are allocated and capitalized to the Connectivity segment based on the relative number of Starlink satellite launches (e.g., an increase from 89 launches in 2024 to 122 in 2025 resulted in relatively more launch operations and overhead costs being capitalized in the Connectivity segment).",
