    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='## Accounting-Policy Question Arising Once Orbital AI Compute Satellite Manufacturing Begins\n\n### Context: A Three-Segment Asset\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) discloses that the company "expect[s] to begin deploying our orbital AI compute satellites as early as 2028." These satellites — defined as satellites with onboard AI processing for inference and other ML workloads in Sun-synchronous orbit — are explicitly described as drawing on **all three reportable segments**:\n\n- **Space segment** — provides the launch (Starship, once commercialized);\n- **Connectivity segment** — provides the integrated satellite manufacturing platform and Starlink low-latency connectivity linking the orbital systems to users; and\n- **AI segment** — operates the compute workloads (inference) and would own the customer-facing AI service.\n\nThis is structurally different from the only internal-satellite precedent in the filing (Starlink), which is a **two-segment** flow (Space launches → Connectivity owns/operates). Orbital AI compute is a **three-segment** flow, and the filing does not specify an accounting policy for it.\n\n### The Central Accounting-Policy Question\n\n**Which segment should capitalize and own the orbital AI compute satellite assets on its balance sheet, and how should the cross-segment inputs — launch services from Space, satellite manufacturing and Starlink connectivity from Connectivity, and compute operations from AI — be accounted for?**\n\nSpecifically, the question has three interrelated sub-components:\n\n1. **Intersegment elimination vs. recognition.** Does the company extend the Starlink precedent (no intersegment revenue recognized; launch costs capitalized directly in the operating segment\'s PP&E) to a three-segment asset, or does the additional Connectivity manufacturing/connectivity input require recognizing an intersegment transfer from Connectivity to AI?\n\n2. **Balance-sheet attribution.** The asset is simultaneously a "satellite" (Connectivity\'s domain, where the Starlink satellite PP&E currently sits) and "AI compute infrastructure" (AI\'s domain). The filing states launch capacity "will be allocated to [the] AI segment in the future" but does not say whether the resulting capitalized asset resides in AI-segment or Connectivity-segment PP&E.\n\n3. **Cost-of-revenue attribution.** The Starship commercialization policy says depreciation flows to "the segment associated with the payload delivered." For an orbital AI compute payload, that points to the AI segment — but the satellite manufacturing and Starlink connectivity inputs originate in Connectivity, creating a tension the filing does not resolve.\n\n### Secondary, Related Questions\n\n- **Useful-life classification.** Is an orbital AI compute satellite depreciated as a *satellite* (3–5 years, driven by propellant/orbit life and on-orbit performance) or as *compute infrastructure* (5–6 years for terrestrial servers/networking), or some hybrid? Radiation/thermal environment may shorten compute life, while chip-obsolescence cycles may precede satellite end-of-life — the two depreciation frameworks point in different directions.\n- **R&D-to-PP&E transition trigger.** Currently all R&D is expensed as incurred, and Starship costs are expensed because Starship is in the development stage. At what point (analogous to Starship\'s "commercialization by delivering payload to orbit" trigger) do orbital AI compute satellite costs move from expensed R&D to capitalized PP&E?\n- **Inventory vs. PP&E.** If any orbital AI compute satellites were sold to third parties rather than operated internally, classification could shift to inventory; the filing\'s framing (internal operation, like Starlink) points to PP&E, but this is not explicitly stated for the AI variant.\n- **Revenue recognition if sold as a service.** If orbital AI compute is sold externally, the API-services policy (usage-based recognition as tokens/compute hours are consumed) and the multi-element arrangement policy (allocating transaction price to distinct performance obligations, per the Starlink customer-contract precedent) would govern top-line recognition — but neither addresses cross-segment cost attribution.\n\n### Most Relevant Disclosed Policies (Ranked)\n\n1. **Intersegment revenue elimination / launch-cost capitalization policy (the "Starlink precedent").** Most directly relevant. The filing states: *"For launches of our Starlink satellites, the Company does not recognize any inter-segment revenue, rather those launch costs are capitalized in satellites in Property, plant, and equipment, net… We allocate a significant amount of launch capacity to our Connectivity segment, and expect to allocate a significant amount to our AI segment in the future."* This is the closest analog and the natural starting point, but it only resolves a two-segment flow and does not address the additional Connectivity manufacturing/connectivity input or the AI-segment balance-sheet attribution.\n\n2. **Starship commercialization / payload-attribution policy.** *"At commercialization, Starship costs generally will be capitalized and then depreciated in cost of revenue of the segment associated with the payload delivered."* This directly bears on which segment\'s cost of revenue absorbs depreciation for orbital AI compute payloads (pointing to AI), and on the R&D-to-PP&E transition trigger.\n\n3. **Satellite capitalization policy (cost composition).** Capitalized satellite costs include build costs (parts, labor, allocated overhead), capitalized launch costs (including an allocation of flight vehicle hardware costs), and capitalized refurbishment/enhancements. This defines the cost basis but does not resolve segment attribution.\n\n4. **Useful-life / depreciation policy.** Broadband satellites: 5 years; first-generation mobile satellites: 3 years; general satellite category: 3–5 years; terrestrial servers/networking: 5–6 years. Determines the depreciation profile but the filing does not specify which category governs orbital AI compute satellites.\n\n5. **Segment measurement and cost-allocation policy.** The CODM measures segments on *income (loss) from operations*; disclosure of allocation methodology is limited (only Space-segment SG&A "allocated employee compensation costs" is described, with no basis disclosed). Relevant because the depreciation and any allocated overhead must land in a specific segment\'s operating result.\n\n6. **R&D expense policy.** All R&D expensed as incurred; Starship costs expensed while in development. Relevant to the transition question (when manufacturing costs cease being R&D and become capitalized PP&E).\n\n7. **Revenue recognition policies for AI services (API usage-based; multi-element allocation).** Relevant only if/when orbital AI compute is sold externally; governs top-line recognition, not the cross-segment cost question.\n\n### What the Filing Does Not Specify\n\nThe S-1 **does not disclose a distinct accounting policy for orbital AI compute satellites or in-space AI assets.** It does not state:\n- which segment\'s balance sheet holds the asset;\n- whether the Starlink no-intersegment-revenue precedent extends to a three-segment asset;\n- the useful life applicable to orbital AI compute satellites;\n- the R&D-to-capitalization transition trigger for these assets; or\n- the methodology for allocating shared manufacturing and launch overhead across the three contributing segments.\n\nAccordingly, the accounting-policy question above is **not resolved by the filing** — it is an open issue that the existing Starlink and Starship-commercialization policies gesture toward but do not settle, precisely because orbital AI compute is the first disclosed asset class that simultaneously consumes inputs from all three reportable segments.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n    